II. THE LEGEND HE WAS (The War-Hound)
Timeline: 40-50 Years Ago
During the height of the Great War and the chaotic years surrounding it, there was no mercenary more feared or respected by the Imperial Legion than the man they called the War-Hound. Bjorn did not march in the ranks; he was a private contractor, a one-man vanguard hired for the impossible tasks that required a level of violence the Empire preferred to keep off the official records.
Born with a dormant Dragon Soul and the blessing of the Steed Stone, Bjorn was a physical anomaly. While other Nords were known for their sturdy, slow-moving bulk, Bjorn was a blur on the battlefield. He possessed a supernatural stride and a limitless reservoir of stamina that allowed him to outrun cavalry and strike with the speed of an arrow. He didn't just fight; he bypassed defenses, appearing in the heart of enemy camps or atop supposedly unreachable battlements before the first horn could even sound.
He was a "War-Hound" in the most literal sense. Once he was shown a targetΓÇöbe it a Thalmor supply line, a hidden fortification, or a high-ranking officerΓÇöhe became a relentless force of kinetic energy. He would run for days without rest, strike with devastating precision, and vanish before the dust settled. The Legionnaires told stories of him clearing entire trenches in the time it took to draw a breath. He wasn't a hero motivated by flags or titles; he was an apex predator who excelled at the trade of death simply because it was the only thing that could keep pace with the fire in his veins. To the generals, he was a perfect tool. To his enemies, he was a ghost that left only corpses in its wake.

III. THE TURNING POINT (The Trauma)
The Failure of the Promise
The War-Hound did not die on a battlefield, and he did not quit because a contract went sour. He retired because he made a personal choice to be more than a weapon, and the world punished him for it with a horror so absolute it redefined his soul.
While traveling through the Cyrodiilic heartland between contracts, Bjorn encountered two young sistersΓÇöpeasant girls orphaned by the fringes of the war. For the first time in his life, the man who only knew how to destroy felt the urge to protect. There was no gold involved, no writ from a general. They approached his camp, hungry, cold. He gave them his word. He sat by them at his fire, shared his bread, and made a solemn, sacred promise: "I am Bjorn, and as long as I am breathing, no harm will ever find you. I will get you to safety." He saw in them a chance for a future that didn't smell of iron and ash.
That promise was his undoing.
The actual snatching happened on a narrow, rain-slicked road in the heart of the Forest. Bjorn was walking between the two sisters, when the noble's hunting party hammered down the path. It was a well-practiced abduction, executed by men who had done this before for their masterΓÇÖs amusement. A heavy carriage, pulled by six black horses bred for stamina and flanked by ten outriders, charged at them with the momentum of a falling mountain.
The outriders didn't draw steel to fight; they used weighted nets and hooked poles. Bjorn reacted with the supernatural reflex of the Steed Stone, striking the first two riders from their mounts, but the carriage did not slow. The doors flew open as it careened past, and the young lord's personal "collectors" leaned out. Bjorn saw it in horrifying detail: the youngest girl snatched by her hair, the older one hauled up by her neck. He lunged, his fingers literally grazing the fabric of the youngest girlΓÇÖs dress, but a heavy iron mace from a trailing outrider caught him in the ribs, throwing him into the dirt and shattering his breath.
He rose before he even hit the ground, his lungs burning with the metallic tang of internal bleeding. He ran. He gave himself entirely to the fire in his soul, his feet hammering the road with such force the gravel sparked. He outran the horses on the flats, his vision tunneling, his heart thumping like a war-drum against his chest. He followed the sound of their distant, receding screams and the frantic thunder of wheels, closing the distance by sheer force of will. He saw the iron gates of the secluded estate begin to swing shut as the carriage cleared the threshold. Bjorn was fifty paces away, moving faster than any man in the history of the Empire, and he watched those gates lock. He threw himself against the cold iron, but the silence of the estate was already absolute. He had pushed his body past the point of structural failure, and he had still been too slow to save them.
He got to work finding his way inside. It took him 2 hours to find a way to breach the estate without raising an alarm and to interrogate enough people to find the tower the girls were in.
He arrived to the tower they were being held in too late.
The Nobel had tortured the girls. The younger one, it looked like he was slowly skinning her, having started on her hands down to her forearms, he had skinned the soles of her feet only, he had also removed her teeth. Bjorn could tell from the bruising and bleeding that the nobel had raped the young girl, likely to death, and based on the semen on her still open eyes he continued to do so after she was already dead. The older one was worse, her eyes had been cut out as had her tongue. Her vagina had been cut out. The hole where it used to be was a mix of blood, shit and semen. Her limbs had been burnt, it looked like she was held down and the nobel used a weak flames spell to slow burn letters into her skin, old cyrodillic, ΓÇ£whore, slut, worthlessΓÇ¥ disgusting things. And she had been cut open. Bjorn had been around he had seen a lot in his time the worst humanity had to offer, so he was 100% certain that the nobel had cut her open and eaten her entrails while she was still alive. Bjorn started to sob.
The sight of what that rich boy had done to those children shattered the War-Hound. All of Bjorn's legendary speed, all his supernatural strength, and all his "destiny" had meant nothing. He had told them they were safe, and they had died in unimaginable agony while he was miles away, being fast at the wrong time.
The violence that followed was not a battle. When the nobleΓÇÖs guards tried to stop him, Bjorn didn't use a sword. He tore through them with his teeth and his grip. He found the young lord in his private chambers. Bjorn didn't arrest him, and he didn't grant him the mercy of a quick death. He systematically dismantled the man with his bare hands, ignoring the boy's screams for mercy or pleas of high-birth.
When the sun rose, the estate was a tomb. Bjorn walked out into the woods, his hands stained with blood that would never feel clean. He realized that the "War-Hound" was a failure at the only thing that actually mattered. He buried his gear, renounced his name, and vanished from the world of men. He didn't just quit a job; he executed the version of himself that believed strength could ever truly protect anything. This trauma is why, even decades later, the darker aspects of his current companions don't rattle himΓÇöbecause he knows that the most polished, "civilized" noble can be a monster far worse than any vampire or mercenary.


IV. THE INTERVENING YEARS (The Healing)
He moved to the Rift. He became a fisherman. And he healed.
He didn't spend 40 years brooding. He spent 40 years learning how to be a person. He learned to love the quiet of the lake. He learned that a good cup of mead tastes better than victory.
The King's Charter: When Torygg was looking for a driver for the Wardens, his advisors dug up the old files. They found the "War-Hound." They expected a killer. Instead, they found a nice old man with a cart. Torygg hired him not because he was a killer, but because Bjorn had the one thing Torygg valued: perspective. Bjorn knew the cost of violence, which made him the perfect guardian for young heroes.

V. THE CONFLICT NOW (The Unwanted Divinity)
This is why the Kynesgrove moment is so tragic.
The Soul Absorption: When Sahloknir died and the soul hit Bjorn, it wasn't a "gift." It was a violation of his peace.
The Physical Change: He feels the aches and pains of age vanishing. His arthritis is gone. His muscles are hard again. He feels the Steed Stone energy surging back, making him fast, making him dangerous.
The Internal Horror: He doesn't want to be young again. He doesn't want to be strong. Being strong means people expect you to fight. Being Dragonborn means he has a "destiny" to save the world.
The Tragedy: He just wanted to drive the cart, joke with Saijah, and pet his horse. Now, the universe is telling him he has to be the War-Hound againΓÇöor something even scarier. He is rejecting his destiny not out of fear, but out of wisdom. He knows that "Hero" is just another word for "Killer," and he's done with killing.
The Party's Role: They aren't just his employers; they are the family he found in his twilight years. He stays with them not to save the world, but because he knows they are going to try to save the world, and he can't bear to watch another group of "kids" die because he wasn't there to protect them.


